abstract: A routine announcement by the Treasury Department about its borrowing plans has attracted more attention than usual because of the rapid rise in interest rates.
snippet: A routine announcement by the Treasury Department about its borrowing plans has attracted more attention than usual because of the rapid rise in interest rates.
lead_paragraph: Investors have fixated this week on a routine quarterly announcement of how the government plans to finance itself, a sign of how sensitive Wall Street has become to a rapid run-up in interest rates.

headline.main: Why Wall Street Is So Worried About ‘Refunding’
headline.print_headline: Why Wall Street Is So Worried About Treasury’s ‘Refunding’

abstract: Two dozen major Wall Street firms sent a letter to top law schools to crack down on discrimination and harassment amid an escalation in incidents targeting Jewish students.
snippet: Two dozen major Wall Street firms sent a letter to top law schools to crack down on discrimination and harassment amid an escalation in incidents targeting Jewish students.
lead_paragraph: With universities across the United States grappling with a rise in antisemitism since the start of the Israel-Hamas war, elite law firms are putting schools on notice. In a letter to some of the nation’s top law schools obtained by DealBook, about two dozen major Wall Street firms warned that what happens on campus could have corporate consequences.

headline.main: Law Firms Warn Universities About Antisemitism on Campus

snippet: The market is focused on making money now and isn’t heeding urgent warnings about climate change, our columnist says.
lead_paragraph: Heat, drought, flood and famine. Evidence of climate change is all around us.

headline.print_headline: In Warming World, Oil Prospers While Clean Energy Sags

abstract: Voters’ negative perceptions about the economy are weighing on President Biden’s poll numbers. Here’s what his economic policies have, and haven’t, accomplished.
snippet: Voters’ negative perceptions about the economy are weighing on President Biden’s poll numbers. Here’s what his economic policies have, and haven’t, accomplished.
lead_paragraph: With a year to go before Election Day, polls increasingly show that American voters believe next year will be a rematch between President Biden and Donald Trump — with the former president in the lead in key battleground states despite his legal troubles (more on that below).

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

abstract: A widely read financial analyst, he was known for his annual forecast “Ten Surprises.” But he was fallible, as when he predicted a President Hillary Clinton.
snippet: A widely read financial analyst, he was known for his annual forecast “Ten Surprises.” But he was fallible, as when he predicted a President Hillary Clinton.
lead_paragraph: At age 80, Byron Wien compiled “20 Life Lessons” from a long career as a Wall Street soothsayer. “Never retire” was No. 20. “If you work forever, you can live forever,’’ he explained. “I know there is an abundance of biological evidence against this theory, but I’m going with it anyway.”

headline.main: Byron Wien, Wall Street Seer of the Unexpected, Dies at 90
headline.print_headline: Byron Wien, 90, Wall Street Seer of the Unexpected

abstract: Shares of smaller companies surged as yields on government bonds tumbled.
snippet: Shares of smaller companies surged as yields on government bonds tumbled.
lead_paragraph: Stocks soared on Tuesday, after an inflation reading raised hopes that the Federal Reserve’s campaign to slow inflation may have reached its limits.

headline.main: Stocks Rally as Inflation Data Cements View the Fed Is Done Raising Rates

abstract: A better-than-expected Consumer Price Index report triggered a big surge in stocks and bonds, as investors bet that interest rates will begin to fall.
snippet: A better-than-expected Consumer Price Index report triggered a big surge in stocks and bonds, as investors bet that interest rates will begin to fall.
lead_paragraph: Yesterday’s impressive rally in U.S. stocks and bonds has gone worldwide this morning, as investors see central banks making gains in their fight against inflation. Adding to the good news was a breakthrough in the House last night that could avert a government shutdown.

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler and Michael J. de la Merced

abstract: The causes Robert F. Kennedy Jr. has championed have brought him admiration, criticism — and tens of millions of dollars.
snippet: The causes Robert F. Kennedy Jr. has championed have brought him admiration, criticism — and tens of millions of dollars.
lead_paragraph: In 2021, Robert F. Kennedy Jr. earned more than $500,000 as the chairman and top lawyer at Children’s Health Defense, the nonprofit organization that he has helped build into a leading spreader of anti-vaccine falsehoods and a platform for launching his independent bid for the White House.

headline.main: How R.F.K. Jr. Has Turned His Public Crusades Into a Private Windfall
headline.print_headline: In Public Causes, Kennedy Earns Acclaim, Criticism and a Fortune

abstract: The financial district is attracting residents who like the charm of the narrow streets and can live with the neighborhood’s lack of sunlight.
snippet: The financial district is attracting residents who like the charm of the narrow streets and can live with the neighborhood’s lack of sunlight.
lead_paragraph: Good morning. It’s Tuesday. We’ll look at the transformation of the financial district, as office buildings are being turned into apartments. We’ll also look at why the Police Department is spending $500 million on new radios.

headline.main: The Neighborhood That’s Shedding Offices for Housing

abstract: After suitors flocked to a sci-fi project by Carl Rinsch, director of a single movie, the winner handed over money and control. They’re still fighting.
snippet: After suitors flocked to a sci-fi project by Carl Rinsch, director of a single movie, the winner handed over money and control. They’re still fighting.
lead_paragraph: Near the height of the streaming boom in the fall of 2018, a half-dozen studios and video platforms lined up to woo a little-known filmmaker named Carl Erik Rinsch. He had directed only one movie, “47 Ronin.” It was a commercial and critical dud, and Mr. Rinsch’s tussles with its producers had raised eyebrows, even in an industry where such conflicts are the norm.

headline.main: The Strange $55 Million Saga of a Netflix Series You’ll Never See
headline.print_headline: $55 Million for a Series, but Not a Single Episode

abstract: The 1968 action led to greater economic mobility for Black workers. Today, union activists are trying to capture some of that spirit.
snippet: The 1968 action led to greater economic mobility for Black workers. Today, union activists are trying to capture some of that spirit.
lead_paragraph: Jack Walker is a union man. He drives a garbage truck in Memphis, where his route can take him barreling past shotgun-style houses along the Mississippi River and down the narrow alleyways near the Lorraine Motel, where the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was assassinated. He is aware, always, of how his union protections are tied to Dr. King’s death and that of another man: his father.

headline.main: How the Memphis Sanitation Workers’ Strike Changed the Labor Movement
headline.print_headline: 55 Years Ago, Tragedy in Memphis Transformed Labor Movement

abstract: Stocks and bonds were buoyed after even inflation-focused Federal Reserve officials suggested that rates may stay steady.
snippet: Stocks and bonds were buoyed after even inflation-focused Federal Reserve officials suggested that rates may stay steady.
lead_paragraph: Federal Reserve officials appear to be dialing back the chances of future interest rate increases, after months in which they have carefully kept the possibility of further policy changes alive for fear that inflation would prove stubborn.

headline.main: Fed Officials Hint That Rate Increases Are Over, and Investors Celebrate
headline.print_headline: Fed Officials Hint That Rate Increases Are Over, Buoying Investors

byline.original: By Jeanna Smialek and Joe Rennison

abstract: Mr. Munger’s death won’t affect the day-to-day operations of the conglomerate, but shareholders will miss his imprint on the company’s ethos.
snippet: Mr. Munger’s death won’t affect the day-to-day operations of the conglomerate, but shareholders will miss his imprint on the company’s ethos.
lead_paragraph: Shares of Berkshire Hathaway barely budged on Wednesday, a day after its vice chairman, Charlie Munger, died, reflecting the view among shareholders that Mr. Munger’s absence on the conglomerate’s day to day would have little impact on its future, even as they mourned the loss of the man who helped shape Berkshire’s culture.

headline.main: With Charlie Munger’s Death, Berkshire Loses a Custodian of Its Culture
headline.print_headline: With Munger’s Death, Berkshire Loses a Custodian of Its Culture
